<DOC><DOCNO> AP890501-0274 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 2223EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Corrigan-Kravis     05-01 0254</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Corrigan-Kravis,0268</SECOND><HEAD>N.Y. Fed President Takes Swipe At Junk Bond King</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A top Federal Reserve official took an impromptuswipe Monday at Henry Kravis, the king of leveraged buyouts.   E. Gerald Corrigan, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of NewYork, noted that Kravis had won an award for leadership in businessin 1988 from Columbia Business School's alumni association.   ``It raises in my mind a question about your definition ofbusiness,'' Corrigan said at the alumni association's 1989 awardsdinner at the Waldorf-Astoria.   The unprepared remark drew murmurs from the black-tie audience.   In his speech, Corrigan said the nation should but more emphasison mechanical and electrical engineering and less on what he calledfinancial engineering.   Across town at the New York Hilton, Kravis was defendingleveraged buyouts as keynote speaker at the annual dinner of theHarvard Business School of Greater New York.   Kravis is a founding partner of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts andamp; Co.,which led such debt-financed deals as the record $24.53 billiontakeover of RJR Nabisco Inc.   ``I see LBOs as one tactic, among others, to free U.S. businessfrom the paralyzing clutches of hidebound corporate bureaucraciesand to increase our competitive position in the world economy,''Kravis said.   At Columbia's dinner, Corrigan received an award for leadershipin government, while Charles E. Exley Jr., chairman and chiefexecutive of NCR Corp., got the award for leadership in businessand W. Edwards Deming, the quality control guru, received alifetime achievement award for public service.</TEXT></DOC>